How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases travel only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very limited.
Czech tourists therefore went from holidays to the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972 when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime turned west and the journeys of Czech tourists were then quite limited.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually by socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at that time, but one should put on the rope with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "known good" in the agency.
Still wasn't earned.
The so-called "change promise" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", which could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of summer houses and houses that the Czechs would acquire.
The way of travel of the Czechs has suffered a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 it was no longer going to spend holidays in RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million trips to countries around the world.
It turns out in a great paradox, from which today we are no longer aware, that Croatia could not travel freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia since then.
In the early 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to neighbouring Western European States, which resulted in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see enough of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least one moment.
For example, in Paris the Czech groups slept in the parks in campaign shops, as our income from that time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was taking with you food (conservations, embuties, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy freely Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it also average wages, which in around 1997 led to an increase in travel demand.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, starting in 1997, regularly to prepare travel using charter flight connections, which made it amazingly lower travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for passenger volume.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had already traveled without visa to almost all developed countries, except the United States, which further simplified our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czechia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have been making distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States eliminated visas for Czech tourists, with what our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 crowns per head on foreign travel, including expenses on the site of stay.
