Climate adversity slowed the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, unemployment and informality have increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment has declined and the economy has been contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-denominated change, which has generated great expectations regarding the economic progress, but given the climate change of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, but a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development is recorded.
The low temperatures in February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the potential of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of overall economic activity of 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly due to the 31.16 per cent fall in agriculture, which affected the dynamics of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of ice impacts issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were damage to 582 000 835 hectares cultivated, 78.03 per cent of which suffered total damage and 21.07 per cent had partial damage, the main sinew crops were vegetables, corn and barley.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was seen as an accelerated growth, since while between January and March 55 000 053 signacles were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, for the second quarter the rate rose to 5.28 per cent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate that in the number of people with over 74 thousand signacles, an increase compared to the first half of 18 000 969 individuals.
Less Liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions taken by public policy.
"What is being seen is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market due to a restriction on resources by the legislation adopted at the congress to combat money laundering, as for people who illegally seize dollars it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something," he said.
Organisation
López Cervantes noted that there is also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people going from the state looking for work abroad in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of the difficulties of entering, and secondly because entering already have many difficulties of finding work, these people are staying and are demanding work sources here in the state, which makes unemployment rising," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloan increased by considering the high level of informality that prevails among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the state-occupied working population without being contributing as a worker to any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the state's labour surpluses is low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Labour Secretariat and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of the workers in Sinaloa was, until September, 5 000 352 pesos, much below the national average, located at 7 000 375 pesos.
IED contraction
As a result of the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, the largest decrease in direct foreign investment over the past 10 years was recorded in 2011 according to the State IED Economic Secretariat from January to June, which amounted to $630,697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent over the $5 million,143,312 recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the State Government's Secretariat for Economic Development accounts for a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pounds per year, mainly of enterprises in the third sector.
The debt
In view of the economic contraction scenario, the Government of the State requested the approval of a loan of 3 billion pounds in July, which would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the economy, the approval of the local congress was at an amount of 2 billion 600 million pounds, and until November they had not observed the benefits of debt in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For business sector representatives, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been very poor, we have to work hard to recover the land that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have to align the effort of all and above all the well-synchronized progress of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said that events such as early-year ice creams stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including ice creams, one of the main effects has been a slow economic turn that does not return fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services, and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing very much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefine job
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Mexican Master's Confederation in Sinaloa, stated that the state is required to engage in productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general, we have observed that we have been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated," he said.
Work to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better matches the Government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the Government has been working hard to deliver good results in various areas, but there are some progress in economic development but it is important that a long-term programme is developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration had made progress in its way of leading public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is becoming more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the Government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
