The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed Italy on the edge of the economic disaster and has put the whole euro area at risk.
A communiqué from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected that he will present an office consisting of most technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the result of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "mark is now well-designed", he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has driven its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by the former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain the strong confidence in Italy.
