MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Directs Social Security an investigation to discover the gender of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute for Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gender of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetic Protocol on Child and Adolescence Obsessiveness', which will allow you to have markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialities of the 21st Century National Medical Centre Miguel Cruz López explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Political Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the participation of the population whether or not they are law-abiding, to visit IMSS participating sports units in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out for minors, every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He noted that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Ponente State of Mexico) and that since 8 October, the activity has been carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (East Mexico State).
Once the goal of meeting 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independent Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research was to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the emergence of degenerative chronic diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day, the goal was to gather three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and history of hereditary diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger suffering such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
It detailed that the Saturdays apply to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure taking, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (it is sought to identify genes associated with child obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in children, of 77 per cent in obesity, and in girls of 47 per cent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed', the IMSS expert pointed out.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers was that the population of the country differs from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent of American Indian inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is translated into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows them to detect whether they have any excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-coloured folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the probability of metabolic changes and even prediabetes.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, who are told each of the measurements and changes in their lifestyle to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic suffering: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM Asphalt Avoids Bakes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemicals Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the floor were attended, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand acres each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemicals Faculty (FQ), who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of an asphaltic floor is the right one, the bricks could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
At its conference A technological opinion of the baches, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of baches.
He explained that asphalt, the most heavy part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, one of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrades its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrades presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but that it is being changed during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible floors, consisting of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
When the vehicles are moved and effort is generated, they allow the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, there is a last layer called rounding folder, which is made of fine stone material, i.e. a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is about the layer that will be in contact with the vehicle’s rims, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
As part of the floor that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling stock also requires adequate thickness and the material it is made must be taken care of.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a resplendent of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of bashes.
In the process of forming a batch, he said, the first to wear is the film of rotation and only then affects the asphalt folder, but the damage does not happen instantly, but it is a process that should address the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
