It is appropriate that an election meeting should be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7. billion people on the planet, demographic developments will result in the duplication of electricity demand by 2050, unless a large proportion of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, there will be an increasing shortage of fossil resources to continue producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
That is neither the case in Belgium, which is subject to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor in Switzerland, which is only intended to build last-generation plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, by quoting some examples, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, on the other hand, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resumes the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such speech.
The Berlin election will result in an increase in the price of electricity, a greater energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, in particular Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions for the construction of gas and coal plants.
Within a few months, the adverse effects will be noted.
You should think about the case of Denmark.
Europe's wind champion, which accounts for 30% of its electricity, is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the persistence of our energy policy, our neighbours are paying an electricity bill of 40% higher than that of the French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and guaranteeing the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would result in a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would remain realistic to the wonderful declarations on the re-industrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not initially object to this type of energy, as the surveys show.
We recall that our country's energy policy has lost the construction of an industrial sector with 125,000 directorial jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets that can create non-localized jobs.
If France had decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would have been the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of EUR 6 billion per year in French nuclear equipment and services exports.
