However, it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
The question is, on this subject, there is a considerable consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation in 1976, stating that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with about two million migrant workers", while on the left, the tone set Michel Rocard explaining that France "could not be responsible for all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish fountainers.
