The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act with regard to immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that the development of co-development will enable the " problem of migration" to be solved.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be economically profitable, but it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the most recent knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migratory flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly those with low qualifications, by pressing for their salaries to be reduced.
However, experience shows that immigrants are actually more complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly engaged in professions in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unqualified immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet staff demand.
A positive effect on salaries
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive impact on the salaries and employment of the nationals.
