North Stream, new Russian gas entry door in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which communicates directly Western Europe with Russia passing through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must provide gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with a great pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, at the opening of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
The German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have swirled together the valve wheel that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western Europe network.
With this new pipeline, it will each year reach 27.5 million cubic metres of additional Russian gas to Western Europe through a first tube of 1,224 km that communicates the San Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, i.e. enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, it is already mentioned the possibility of building a third tube through the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time of this huge work presents the air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow direct supply of gas to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening it to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy since the project has created a gap between the Europeans of the East and the West.
Russia has known, in just five years, to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is part of our association with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," said François Fillon during the launch of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles in the faces of the Gazprom directors, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-covered steel to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It is located at the bottom of the sea, an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines that date from World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, with caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream.
It was also necessary to extend measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but the project's managers also gave up on the fact that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be permanently established at sea in front of its shores.
"In case of emergency, we will stop the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of escape, the gas pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a flight will occur, since they have planned mergers that, according to the forecasts, they will have a flight every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline shall be ensured by means of a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device flowing through the interior of the pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it enters the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three complete days of travel at a speed of three metres per second, provide precise data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for any type of repair.
Gas circulation is guaranteed only by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and at the output of 100 bars.
Five companies have united their forces to be able to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which holds 51% of the stakes.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each), joined her.
These five companies have created a common company, called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to that company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, the total capacity of gas transport.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and by 70% with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7,400 million for both pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are certain that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom assumes on its own the risk of expenditure.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted by pines.
Some valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the gas output door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
Total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
