A success that provokes envy: in the fall of 2006, Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of people with disabilities are seeking employment.
The XV Week for the Employment of Persons with Disabilities begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Dissolved?
"No," said Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made 15 years ago is considerable.
"At that time the unemployment rate was not twice as high as the average, but three times as high as the average.
"However, there's still a lot to do."
It should be noted that the unemployed continue to face numerous obstacles to accessing employment.
They usually have a more advanced age: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed the bachelor's degree and only 10,000 of the 2.3 million students in higher education are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for disabled people, compared to 38 per cent of the average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the labour world and that "constitute the quoy of the problem", says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplín, an association created in 1992 to help businesses hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality progresses, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur Association for the City indicated that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set out in a... 1987 law.
According to the latest available figures, which date from 2008, a ratio of 2.6% is reached.
"Now we reach about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishments "submitted to this contribution" as well as the amounts disbursed has decreased between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, has created great pressure for businesses," Pierre Blanc explains.
"But this improvement also reflects a true awareness, particularly among the major groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of the companies with between 20 and 49 workers have employees with disabilities in their template, compared to 82 per cent of businesses with between 100 and 199 workers.
